# Pattern: PR previews — one live environment per open pull request

Argo CD's native answer to "deploy every PR, tear it down on merge/close" — and
the reason this stack runs Argo CD rather than a push-based reconciler. An
**ApplicationSet** with a **PullRequest generator** watches an app repo, stamps
out one `Application` per open PR into its own namespace, and **prunes it
automatically when the PR closes**. That auto-pruning is the structural fix for
the disk-pressure outage (`runbooks/incidents/disk-pressure.md`): dead previews
can no longer pile up, because nobody has to remember to clean them.

This is **pull-based**: Argo CD reads the PR branches itself. The app's CI never
gets cluster credentials — no `kubectl`, no `KUBECONFIG`, no `id-token` for the
cluster (AGENTS.md inv. 1). It only builds and pushes the image.

## 1. The app repo carries a preview overlay

Alongside `deploy/overlays/production`, the app repo adds
`deploy/overlays/preview`. It must be **self-contained per PR** so previews
never collide:

```
deploy/overlays/preview/
  kustomization.yaml      # nameSuffix / namespace come from the PR (see below)
  deployment.yaml         # image: ghcr.io/{{ github_owner }}/<app>  (CI sets the tag)
  service.yaml
  ingress.yaml            # host: <app>-pr-<n>.{{ domain }} ; issuer: acme
```

Keep previews cheap: one replica, `revisionHistoryLimit: 2`,
`progressDeadlineSeconds: 300` (same discipline `new-app.sh` bakes into in-repo
apps — disk-pressure prevention).

## 2. Register the ApplicationSet

`scripts/new-app.sh <app> --repo https://github.com/{{ github_owner }}/<app>`
writes **two** files into `apps/`:

- `apps/<app>.yaml` — the production `Application` (push to `main` → rollout);
- `apps/<app>-previews.yaml` — the preview `ApplicationSet` (below). Pass
  `--no-previews` to skip it, or `--preview-path` to point elsewhere than
  `deploy/overlays/preview`.

{% raw %}
```yaml
apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: ApplicationSet
metadata:
  name: <app>-previews
  namespace: argocd
spec:
  goTemplate: true
  goTemplateOptions: ["missingkey=error"]
  generators:
    - pullRequest:
        github:
          owner: <owner>
          repo: <app>
          # tokenRef:                        # private repo / rate limits:
          #   secretName: <owner>-argocd-secret   # the GitHub App secret
          #   key: githubAppPrivateKey            # (runbooks/argocd-github-app.md)
        requeueAfterSeconds: 60
  template:
    metadata:
      name: '<app>-pr-{{ .number }}'
    spec:
      project: community
      source:
        repoURL: https://github.com/<owner>/<app>
        targetRevision: '{{ .head_sha }}'   # the PR's HEAD, re-synced on every push
        path: deploy/overlays/preview
      destination:
        server: https://kubernetes.default.svc
        namespace: '<app>-pr-{{ .number }}'
      syncPolicy:
        automated:
          prune: true        # converge the namespace to the PR's manifests
          selfHeal: true
        syncOptions:
          - CreateNamespace=true
```
{% endraw %}

When a PR closes, the generator stops emitting its entry; the ApplicationSet
deletes the `Application`, whose `resources-finalizer` prunes everything it
created (deployment, service, ingress, certificate). On a new commit, Argo
re-syncs the same namespace to the new `head_sha` — old pods are replaced, not
accumulated.

## 3. Filter which PRs get a preview (optional)

To preview only PRs that opt in (cheaper on a single node), label them and add
a filter:

```yaml
  generators:
    - pullRequest:
        github:
          owner: <owner>
          repo: <app>
          labels:
            - preview
        requeueAfterSeconds: 60
```

Now only PRs carrying the `preview` label get an environment.

## 4. Per-PR hostname & TLS

The preview ingress should use a per-PR host so each environment is reachable
and gets its own certificate, e.g. `<app>-pr-<n>.{{ domain }}` (covered by the
`*.{{ domain }}` wildcard DNS, issuer `acme`). Derive `<n>` in the preview
overlay from the namespace, or template it via the ApplicationSet (an extra
parameter on the generator). Keep the issuer named `acme` (AGENTS.md).

## Why this replaced push-based previews

The previous (Flux-era) design had the app's CI `kubectl apply` previews using a
namespace-scoped `preview-deployer` RoleBinding. Pull-based previews remove that
cluster credential from CI entirely and make cleanup automatic instead of a
workflow step that could be forgotten — which is exactly how the disk-pressure
incident happened. The `preview-deployer` ClusterRole still ships
(`cluster/rbac/`) for any app that genuinely needs push access, but previews no
longer require it.
